The Manual Rollout
Scenario
You are managing a production server running a critical application (v2.1.3). A severe bug has been reported, and the development team has pushed a patch image: myapp:v2.1.4.

Because this environment relies on manual Docker containers instead of an orchestrator, you cannot perform a "Rolling Update." You must perform a manual replacement of the container. This scenario demonstrates the high-stress environment of manual operations where service downtime is inevitable during updates.

Task
Working directory: /home/user

1. Verification:

Check the currently running container named api-container. Confirm it is running the old image (v2.1.3).
2. The Manual Update:

Stop the running container to release the port.
Remove the stopped container to free up the name api-container.
Start a new container using the same name (api-container) but with the new image (myapp:v2.1.4).
You MUST manually ensure the new container matches the exact production configuration:
Port Mapping: Host 8080 to Container 8080
Restart Policy: unless-stopped
Mode: Detached (-d)
Expected Outcome
The container api-container is active and running image myapp:v2.1.4.
Learning Note: Notice that between the "Stop" and "Start" commands, your application was completely offline. This "downtime gap" is a major risk in manual operations that Orchestration solves.
